<$fill $name="body">

!! Module discovery

Type handlers are discovered at widget-instantiation time via:

```js
$tw.modules.getModulesByTypeAsHashmap("scribetype")
```

The returned hashmap is keyed by `exports.name` — same convention TW core uses for `tiddlerfield`, `filteroperator`, etc.

!! Refresh semantics

`Widget.refresh(changedTiddlers)` is called by TW's reactivity system whenever any tiddler in `changedTiddlers` is one we depend on. We watch:

* The state tiddler — change here means the user (or another widget) edited the input
* The target tiddler — change here means an external source updated the field

We do NOT call `refreshSelf()` for state/target changes; we only re-prep state or write field, then call `refreshChildren()`. This keeps the input widget mounted (no focus loss).

!! Avoiding write loops

`prepState()` does a `deepEqual()` comparison before writing the state, and `writeFromState()` doesn't re-trigger `prepState()` for the same value (the `lastValue` cache). Together these break the potential A→B→A→B loop where writing one side would re-trigger writing the other.

!! Path-walking JSON

`readCurrentValue()` does `JSON.parse(fieldText)` then walks the path array, indexing strings into either `Object` keys or `Array` positions. Numeric strings are valid array indices in JS, so `obj["0"]` works the same as `obj[0]`.

`writeFromState()` walks the same path on a freshly-parsed copy, creating intermediate `{}` or `[]` containers as needed (chooses array if the next path segment is purely digits). This means you can write to a brand-new deep sub-path without pre-creating parents.

!! Empty-state means "delete" (the asymmetric case)

For an OBJECT parent, `delete parent[key]` removes the key entirely.

For an ARRAY parent, we set `parent[idx] = ""` rather than `splice()` because shifting array indices would invalidate any other scribes pointing at later positions in the same array. This is a tradeoff: it preserves callers but leaves an empty-string slot. For most use cases (the kind plugin's per-cell editing) this is fine — the property goes from "set to something" to "empty string", which existing readers treat as missing.

